 "source": "Weld-Blundell Prism (WB 444), after S. Langdon, Oxford Editions of Cuneiform Texts II: Historical Inscriptions (Oxford, 1923), Col. I. Cuneiform shown in normalized Unicode (Neo-Assyrian sign forms) though the prism is Old Babylonian. Academic transliteration in modern subscript notation over Langdon's 1923 readings; pronunciation is conventional and reconstructed. Translations made fresh from the Sumerian.",
 "about": "This is the world's oldest surviving list of kings, copied c. 1800 BCE onto a clay prism now in the Ashmolean Museum. Everything here is a reconstruction: the reading of individual signs, their values, the word-divisions, the pronunciation, even the giant numbers are scholarly conventions — and some are frank best-guesses. The reader-facing text follows Langdon's 1923 edition; where a reading is genuinely uncertain the notes say so, and one line whose royal name Langdon himself flagged is shown as 'glyphs pending'.",
