   "ln": 1,
   "t": "𒉆𒈗 𒀭𒋫 𒂊𒉈𒀀𒁀",
   "l": "kingship — from heaven when-it-came-down —",
   "i": "When kingship came down from heaven,",
   "n": "The famous opening. nam- is the abstract-noun prefix ('king' → 'king-ship'); -ta is the ablative 'from'; an is 'heaven / sky'. The verb e₃ 'go up/down' takes the nominalizer -a and -ba 'in that (time)': 'when (kingship) had descended.' You will meet nam-, -ta and -a constantly. Honest crux: the sign read here as e₃ (𒂊, plain E) is one of several conventional spellings of this verb.",
